<td width="33"><img src="/images/clear.gif" width=33 height=1 border="0"></td>
<td>
<a name="PQN274005"></a>
<br>
<span class="headline">Role Playing Server?</span><br>
<span class="byline">3/24/01, 7:23 PST | <a href="mailto:kwill@rpgplanet.com">Kwill</a></span><br><br>
<span class="newsitem">The idea of a role playing server, which would be somehow different from the other servers in the game, is garnering a lot of attention from posters to the official Sony boards.  Brad (Aradune) started the discussion with this comment in his question and answer session:<blockquote>We've not only responded to this, I'm even pretty sure it's in the FAQ. The answer is, no one can
                       agree on what an 'RP' server would be, or what we'd enforce or change to make it (or EQ in general)
                       more of an RP game. I can tell you what I'd do to make EQ more of an RP game, but I'm sure many of
                       you would respond quite negatively to my ideas.<br><br>

                       But, hey, here are just a few:<br><br>

                       1. Implement Trivial Combat code everywhere<br>
                       2. Eliminate the common tongue<br>
                       3. Allow only one character per server<br>
                       4. Disallow Paladins grouping with Shadow Knights, etc.<br>
                       5. Make it so evil races cannot communicate with good, and vice versa.<br><br>

                       Anyway, those are just off the top of my head. Those would make EQ more of a role-playing game in
                       my opinion. But I bet a lot of people will really disagree with me, and of course I need to type in a big
                       disclaimer here: these are just my opinions and are NOT changes coming to an EQ near you.</blockquote>Brad's opinion or not, this comment has generated a thread that has now been split into three parts.  Most posters are overwhelmingly positive about the idea, with quite a few people claiming they would move to such a server if it was ever created.<br><br>The implementation of PvP on such a server has generated the most controversy, with some for, and some against.  The question arises of how role playing involves PvP.  Should you be able to kill only the opposite of your own faction (good or evil)? Or kill those of your own race as well?  Should you be able to help someone who is opposed to you?  There are no easy answers to the PvP problem, as those who are interested in it well know.<br><br>The one-character-per-server idea seems to have had a positive response.  The players who posted to this forum, for the most part, like the idea of not having an alternate character to play.  This is surprising, considering how many people play more than one character. It might be easier to invest time and a personality into a character on a server that would expect you to act according to your race and religious beliefs.<br><br>For the most part, players have adjusted to the idea that all characters can group, regardless of whether when they were created they were "good" or "evil".  The idea of role playing is swallowed up in the larger goals of getting levels and "phat lewtz".  There are a few role players out there, but they certainly struggle against the tide of game play being mainly "out of character".  Even the role players seem to group with those who in a true role-playing environment they would consider arch-enemies.  Brethon's post on the thread sums up some of the ideas about a role playing server:<blockquote>I would definitly switch to a server with this idea, just because it would bring a new aspect of fun to
                       the game and really be a huge change from what it is now. There'd be a lot of people who wouldn't
                       follow the RP guidelines, but the one character per person, no common tongue and all the other
                       rules/restrictions that could be implimented would make up for it, so I guess a RP server really could
                       work under those conditions, however if it was just a server with GMs enforcing rules by how they
                       saw RPing it would not work, and labelling a server as RP when it is exactly the same as other servers
                       (game wise) would do nothing. Would be nice to see some of these ideas people are suggesting
                       implemented. I would play there for sure.</blockquote>Would a role playing server work?  It's possible, but with so many opinions about what role playing is, it would inevitably be changed from where it began by the players themselves.  In the end, it would be up to the server populations, not the rule-makers, to make such an idea be truly fun for  the player base.<br><br>If you would like to join the discussion on the Sony boards, <a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/070376.html" target="_top">click here.</a></span><br><br>
</td>
<td width="10"><img src="/images/clear.gif" width=10 height=1 border="0"></td>
</tr>
