<td width="33"><img src="/images/clear.gif" width=33 height=1 border="0"></td>
<td>
<a name="PQN273988"></a>
<br>
<span class="headline">Conversations With Absor</span><br>
<span class="byline">3/23/01, 11:35 PST | <a href="mailto:kwill@rpgplanet.com">Kwill</a></span><br><br>
<span class="newsitem"><b>Development note</b>:  VI is implementing emote messages about sucess or failure when doing trade skills to all players rather than just the crafter.<br><br><b>On the Casual Gamer:</b><blockquote>A brownie-00 writes:<i> I think I have a suitable solution for the Casual Player vs PowerGamer argument. Please take a
                       moment to read and comment if you so desire.

                       All players want the same thing from the game... better loot and more levels. The difference is that
                       the "Powergamer" (PG) can reach this goal much, much faster than the "Casual Player" (CP).
                       Additionally, many things simply cannot be obtained by a CP.  Why is there only ONE way to obtain anything in EverQuest?</i><br><br>Absor replies:  I, too, disagree with your basic assumption that casual gamers want the same things from a game
                       that power gamers do. I could (and have) write pages about how I disagree.

                       But I wouldn't disagree with the conclusion you make. It would be nice if there were alternate ways
                       to achieve a single goal. But there is a problem: How do you achieve that goal?<br><br>

                       Let us assume that there is a simple quest that, for example, required a large number of people to go
                       defeat a monster and bring something back. The reason that it requires a lot of people is that the
                       monster is mind-numbingly hard to kill. So the reward is going to be excellent. <br><br>

                       This is a simple quest. The trick is, how do you make the same quest more time consuming and just
                       as difficult (to warrant the same reward), but only requires six people to accomplish? I am assuming
                       that the reason that you claim such a thing is out of the reach of a casual player is because he can't
                       gather a group large enough to defeat the mind-numbingly powerful NPC (though I could argue that
                       too).<br><br>

                       I have not seen a method for doing this that meets a few important criteria.<br><br>

                       It can't be overly out of character in its limitations.<br>
                       It can't be more easily done by the large group of power gamers that would normally do the single
                       encounter.<br>
                       The challenge must be worthy of the awesome reward.<br><br>

                       Ok, I could only think of two off the top of my head, but there will be more that pop up later 
<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/070231.html" target="_top">The entire thread is here.</a></blockquote><b>On Scantily Clad Elves:</b><blockquote>A player objected to the scantily clad NPC models and asked if they could have some clothes put on...Absor asked for the names of the npcs the player  was talking about: <i> "I'm asking you to tell me where these nekkid elves are. Each character has a name, I would like you
                       to give me the name of such a character. The reason I am asking this is because I know that there
                       are none. I just want to assure you of that fact.<br><br>


                       As to those that think I'm wasting my time here where I should be answering other questions... I am
                       answering other questions. I'm just not answering screams, yells, insults or other such things."</i></blockquote><b>On Roleplaying:</b><blockquote>

                     ...  I'll explain why I think removing bottom feeding has a LOT to do with RP. When I'm in a dungeon
                     adventuring and I encounter farmers and other characters too high level, it abruptly and forcefully removes me
                     from suspension of disbelief -- it severely damagers the immersiveness of the game. And I think that's directly
                     tied to RP, just as some guy using d00d speak hurts an RP environment, or seeing a Troll ally with a Paladin. <br><br>

                     In D&D, it just wouldn't be allowed. No DM worth his salt would allow a group of level 8 players to slaughter
                     through a level 2 module... and even worse, to allow another low level group in the module simultaneously.<br><br>

                     Or how about from fantasy literature... how 'RP' would it have been if, as the hobbits were fighting against
                     goblins and wolves, they rounded a bend in the forest to find a group of Valar slaugtering the evil denziens with
                     blinks of their eyes? <br><br>

                    
                     By the way, I'll hereby slightly adjust our opinion as it relates to an RP server... <br><br>

                     Now that we have so many servers, perhaps it wouldn't be so dangerous to set up a server with a slightly
                     different ruleset and call it an RP server... even though many, many would disagree with the ruleset (whether it
                     was fair, or truly RP, or whatever), there are perhaps enough people now who play this game that we could fill
                     the server...<br><br><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/069048.html" target="_top">Read ideas about a role playing server here.</a></blockquote></span><br><br>
</td>
<td width="10"><img src="/images/clear.gif" width=10 height=1 border="0"></td>
</tr>
